I'll help you build a comprehensive roadmap for your Dubai-to-Kampala car import and ecommerce business. This is an exciting venture with real potential in Uganda's growing market. Let me break down everything you need to know:

BUSINESS FOUNDATION
Market Research & Validation

Uganda's used car market is heavily reliant on imports (Japan, UAE being top sources)
Dubai offers competitive pricing, newer models, and right-hand drive vehicles
Your target customers: middle-income professionals, businesses needing fleet vehicles, diaspora buyers
Key competitors: established importers at Luzira/Nakawa, online platforms like Cheki Uganda, Jiji
Your edge: Direct Dubai sourcing cuts middlemen, ecommerce adds convenience, transparency builds trust
Legal Structure & Registration

Register with Uganda Registration Services Bureau (URSB) as a limited company
Obtain Trading License from Kampala Capital City Authority (KCCA)
Register for Tax Identification Number (TIN) with Uganda Revenue Authority (URA)
Get Import/Export License from Ministry of Trade
Register with Uganda Revenue Authority as an importer
Consider joining Uganda Automotive Importers Association for industry support
IMPORT LOGISTICS & OPERATIONS
Dubai Sourcing Strategy

Establish relationships with UAE car dealers and auction houses (Copart UAE, Emirates Auction)
Visit Dubai initially to vet suppliers - avoid scams
Key sourcing areas: Sharjah (budget vehicles), Dubai Auto Zone, Ras Al Khor
Hire a Dubai-based inspection agent or partner (mandatory for quality control)
Vehicles should be 2015 or newer ideally - Uganda buyers prefer relatively recent models
Focus on popular brands: Toyota (Harrier, Land Cruiser, Premio), Nissan, Honda, Subaru
Shipping & Freight

Main route: Jebel Ali Port (Dubai) ‚Üí Mombasa Port (Kenya) ‚Üí Kampala by road
Shipping time: 3-4 weeks by sea freight
Partner with reliable freight forwarders (get 3-4 quotes)
Shipping costs: approximately $800-$1,500 per vehicle depending on size
Consider RORO (Roll-on/Roll-off) for cost efficiency vs container shipping
Insurance: Get comprehensive marine insurance for transit
Clearing & Compliance in Uganda

Import Duties & Taxes:

Import Duty: 25% of CIF (Cost + Insurance + Freight)
VAT: 18% of (CIF + Import Duty)
Withholding Tax: 6% of CIF
Environmental Levy: Based on engine capacity
Infrastructure Levy: 1.5% of CIF
Total taxes typically 50-60% of vehicle cost
Required Documentation:

Bill of Lading
Commercial Invoice
Export Certificate from Dubai
Pre-shipment Verification of Conformity (PVoC) certificate
Insurance Certificate
Original logbook/title from UAE
Import Declaration Form (IDF)
Clearing Process:

Hire a licensed clearing agent at Mombasa (essential - don't skip this)
Vehicle inspection by Uganda National Bureau of Standards (UNBS)
Payment of duties to URA
Registration with Uganda Revenue Authority
Road worthiness test
Registration with Ministry of Works & Transport
Number plates from URA
FINANCIAL PLANNING
Startup Capital Breakdown (Estimated)

Initial Investment: UGX 150-200 million ($40,000-$53,000)

First inventory (3-5 cars): UGX 100-140 million
Business registration & licenses: UGX 2-3 million
Website development: UGX 3-5 million
Physical yard/showroom deposit: UGX 10-15 million
Marketing launch: UGX 5-8 million
Working capital (operations): UGX 15-20 million
Contingency (15%): UGX 15-20 million
Per-Vehicle Economics Example:

Dubai purchase price: $8,000
Shipping & insurance: $1,200
Clearing & duties (55%): $5,060
Agent fees, transport, inspection: $800
Total landed cost: $15,060 (‚âàUGX 56 million)
Retail price: UGX 70-75 million
Gross profit per vehicle: UGX 14-19 million
Net profit margin target: 15-20% after overhead
Funding Options:

Personal savings + family/friends investment
Bank loans (dfcu, Centenary, Stanbic have SME products - expect 18-24% interest)
Uganda Development Bank for manufacturing/trade ventures
Angel investors or business partners
Start small (1-2 cars) and reinvest profits
